definition: "Fasting glucose is a measurement of blood glucose concentration after an overnight fast of at least 8 hours, during which no caloric intake has occurred. In the fasted state, blood glucose is maintained within a narrow range through the coordinated action of insulin (which drives glucose into cells), glucagon (which stimulates hepatic glucose output), and the liver's glycogen stores. The value reflects the set point at which the body's glucose-regulating machinery has settled during the overnight period — a direct window into the health of insulin signaling, hepatic glucose handling, and pancreatic beta cell function. Fasting glucose is the most commonly ordered metabolic test in clinical medicine and is part of every comprehensive metabolic panel (CMP), basic metabolic panel (BMP), and standard annual physical blood panel. It is used to diagnose diabetes (≥ 126 mg/dL on two occasions), prediabetes (100–125 mg/dL), and normal glucose tolerance (< 100 mg/dL per standard definitions)."
why_it_matters: "The standard clinical cutoffs for fasting glucose — normal < 100 mg/dL, prediabetes 100–125 mg/dL, diabetes ≥ 126 mg/dL — were designed to identify people who already have significant metabolic dysfunction. Longevity medicine operates on different logic: at what glucose level does biological aging begin to accelerate, and how far below the 'normal' cutoff is optimal? The epidemiological answer is clear: fasting glucose shows a continuous dose-response relationship with cardiovascular mortality that begins well below the diabetic or prediabetic range. Multiple large cohort studies including the Whitehall II study, the European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition (EPIC), and the Health Professionals Follow-Up Study found that fasting glucose in the 90–99 mg/dL range — technically 'normal' — was associated with meaningfully higher cardiovascular risk and all-cause mortality compared to values in the 70–85 mg/dL range. The implication is that the normal reference range masks a longevity-significant gradient: there is no safe floor within 'normal,' and optimal is substantially lower than most people assume."

